# AI-Generated Code Verification

When generating code, explicitly mark things that require human verification. Don't produce confident-looking code that contains non-obvious assumptions.

## Always flag

### Ordering dependencies
If the correctness of an operation depends on execution order, say so:
```ts
// VERIFY: message deletion must happen AFTER datapoint deletion
// to avoid orphaned messages. See deleteOrphanedResources.ts pattern.
await deleteDatapoints(userId);
await deleteMessages(userId);
```

### Cross-team impact
If a change touches a shared interface, query, or table used by multiple teams:
```ts
// VERIFY: this query is used by Goomba, Pikachu, Resetti, Waluigi teams.
// Confirm change is safe for all consumers before merging.
```

### Performance assumptions
If you've written a query or operation that may degrade at scale:
```ts
// VERIFY: this adds a JOIN that may be 10-20x slower at scale.
// Check pganalyze / Datadog before enabling for high-traffic orgs.
```

### Non-obvious boolean/state logic
If the logic encodes a subtle domain rule that isn't obvious from the code:
```ts
// VERIFY: tokenCount === 2 means unique identifier (3 = shared).
// This is a storage artifact — see LinkedIdentifier value object proposal.
```

### Destructive operations
Any delete, truncate, or irreversible mutation:
```ts
// VERIFY: this deletes records. Confirm idempotency and
// that re-running won't delete valid data.
```

## Don't over-flag

Only flag things that genuinely require human judgment. Don't add VERIFY comments to standard patterns that are obviously correct — that trains people to ignore them.
